

<p>I whipped up a script this morning to simulate Finder&rsquo;s &ldquo;Open With&hellip;&rdquo; menu from the command line. It extends the macOS <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">open</code> command with a command line menu selection of apps able to open the file you specify.</p>

<p>This script uses the macOS commands <a href="https://ss64.com/mac/mdfind.html" title="mdfind man page">mdfind</a> and <a href="https://ss64.com/mac/open.html" title="open man page">open</a>, along with the third-party utilities <a href="https://github.com/moretension/duti" title="duti UTI explorer">duti</a> and <a href="https://github.com/junegunn/fzf" title="A command-line fuzzy finder">fzf</a> or <a href="https://github.com/charmbracelet/gum" title="charmbracelet/gum:A tool for glamorous shell scripts">gum</a>.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight fixed"><code>find <span class="nb">.</span> <span class="nt">-name</span> <span class="s1">'*.rb'</span> | fzf | open-with</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Produces:</p>

<p><img src="https://cdn3.brettterpstra.com/uploads/2025/11/open-with.svg"></p>

<p>I&rsquo;m going to paywall this one as bonus content for my supporters. <a href="https://brettterpstra.com//support/">Join at any level</a> to get the script.</p>

